reviews.text: A good place for trekking and to experience the nature at its best. They have an entrance fee for mossy forest. If you're an adventure freak then better to trek all the way to here but don't forget to bring some warm clothes as this place gets really cold in the mornings.

Beautiful walk up the mountain. Easily doable. Most of the locals are willing to take you down if you are too tired to walk back down. On the way there are plenty of beautiful plants and animals to spot. The entrance to the actual Forrest on top is 30MYR which I found a bit high for what it is.

Worth to go ! Well organized but the track is quite short. Hope it will extend longer in the future.

Driving to there is quite harsh, need to be careful.
A must visit for anyone who enjoys nature. Many rare plants which would be difficult to find anywhere else in the region. Also a fantastic view of the area.

As they say this is one of oldest forest in the world, however we didn't get a chance to see it completely as due to rain there were damp mud all over place and you are unable to walk further.
But still we get a chance to see it small enough and it was good. All trees covered in green algae type thing and ferns were growing on stem, it was pretty.

We did the full day Explorer tour with Francis as our guide. On this particular tour, other than an hour in the tea factory, you're outdoors and walking all day. We fancied that rather than the other full day tours which take you to museums, strawberry farms etc. We were picked up promptly at 0845 and the six of us in the Land Rover were driven to our first viewpoint of the tea fields. Here, Francis gave us plenty of interesting info on the BOH tea plantations and we then drove to the tea factory for a tour around.

We had a walk in the mossy forest for an hour or two, which was amazing. It's not the boardwalk route that you have to pay entry for, but a much more natural and much more impressive section of the forest - there was lots of climbing and crouching involved! We definitely couldn't have done this section without a guide either. After lunch we walked up the third highest peak in the region, which was pretty strenuous but rewarding. Throughout the walks Francis told us interesting stuff about the nature around us; we were dropped back off at our hostel at about 1600.

I thought this was good value for a whole day (100RM) and would recommend it if you're in the Cameron Highlands!

We did the half day mossy forest tour.

Our tour guide was half an hour late to pick us up from our hotel which wasn’t a pleasant start to the tour

Our tour guide did not bring us to the mossy forest! He instead suggested a private forest the company owned, our group decided this would be ok instead. This was a direct uphill walk that no one in our group was prepared for and after a couple of days of rainfall it was dangerously slippery. The view was nice, but not what we signed up for.

The tea plantations were lovely and the strawberry farm! We were able to try unique tea and starwaberry products.

Avoid the butterfly farm if possible, the animals in the zoo area were not well and a couple were dead in the cages.

Very enjoyable tour. Our guide was Satya, a very knowledgeable man that was able to answer to all questions that came along. He's also a professional photographer and has taken part in many researches so he told us a lot of interesting facts and info about the fauna and flora existing around and in other places and could accompany the explanations with amazing pictures taken by him. The activity that the company is taking to protect and preserve the forest is also admirable. Totally recommended.

We booked the fill day tour for 90 RM. Our guide was nice. His english was really good.

The tour was ok. Maybe it could be organized more like an event (with a good place to eat and more storytelling about the region etc.) than just bringing the participants to nice spots and tell them like: "meet here again in 40minutes, enjoy your time."

A point we really disliked was the butterfly farm visit. This is actually a little zoo with Butterflies (which all looked not healthy, a lot of them were dead), but also other insects and animals which had to live under horrible conditions (small and dirty cages with nothing but a bit to eat and drink). This has nothing to do with eco. 
Q10

Problem was the traffic (which is not the company's fault).

We had a very nice trip on the half day "Mossy Forest" tour. 
After being picked up with a Landrover at our hotel meeting our little group for the tour, we started with a hike into the mossy forest, where our guide Balla explained everything about the local flora and fauna and didn't make too many jokes on our inappropriate footwear ;)
On our following way to a local tea factory we could enjoy the nice views over the tea plantages covering the surrounding highlands.
The tour through the factory showed all the steps during the processing of the tea leaves after which we've been brought home (via several stops at different shops, that wouldn't have been necessary, but didn't hurt either).
The time tunnel is no more  it was destroyed by a large fire sometime last month (March 2018)
Travel back in time here. It's remembered us to our very young time in 1970's and 1980's. Have lot of stuffs for us to think back.

Quiet enviroment , very cold .. got a nice breakfast at here. Very good worker at here. Nice nature view . I pray to Allah will give u good health coz u dont care spent a money about the breakfast. Hope i can came again.. 🤗

Love love loveeee the place. Beautifull. Need to maintain a bit. Bed a bit dusty. But yeah tepuk2 the bed gone already la the dust. Bathroom locks need to check. Go with family ok la dont have lock . LOL.  Considering the price, need a little bit more accomodation BUT STILLL NICE PLACE TO STAY.  Except the entrace. So gayat and high.
This is our fourth time here.beautiful ambience,quaint and picturesque.if you like Tudor style then this is the right choice.staffs are friendly.good service.definitely will be our favourite spot
The place is quaint. You feel time stands still here. If you like British colonial building, this place is a must visit. The view is magnificent.

Ambience: 4/5
Service: 3/5

Thumbs up:
- The place exudes old English charm with awesome cool weather
- Spacious room

Thumbs down:
- The place looks like it needs some upkeep. Somewhat rundown
- Room floor is gritty. No room slippers so you’d end up tracking dirt onto the bed
- Bedsheets not really clean

Good food! 
Portion are suitable, not too big or small for normal people.
Pricing is worth coz their foods are delicious.

Dont expect city service in this small town then it deserves 5 star.
I had smoked duck and it was great!
Nice and cozy place to dine in. Friendly staff and a cheaper price. I like their flame duck.
Their famous Duck Breast dish.
one of the best food and cafe in cameron highland......

The food here is awesome. Very authentic Indian food and feeling. The service was good and friendly. Prices are very good.
I went there at least 3 times in 3 days. Probably because they sell beer!! (Most other places are halal = no alcohol)

Good authentic food at very reasonable prices. Excellent service as well. Will definitely come back here the next time we're in Cameron Highlands.

Dec 2108 Update: Still the best place for south indian food in Cameron Highlands. Excellent service, delicious food and very reasonable pricing. I'd give them another star if I could.
The restaurant was so busy but the food was not as good as we expected. The owner and staffs were so friendly so I gave them a 3 out of 5
Ate several times here. Everything fresh and carefully prepared, people smiling. Best mutton murtagh and freshly oven baked naan bread :) Highly recommended!

The food is fairly expensive and not very good. Prices in Brinchang or Tanah Rata is quite high everywhere, so the food could at least be good. But this was bland and oily. They even asked if I'm ok with spicy and I said yes, but it wasn't spicy even a little.
